Note:
COBOL Comprehensive Test Suite Runner

Runs all COBOL test suites:
1. Lexer tests (comprehensive tokenization)
2. Parser tests (AST generation)
3. HIR translation tests (AST → HIR)
4. Code generation tests (HIR → COBOL)
5. Round-trip translation tests (COBOL → HIR → COBOL)

Total: 50+ comprehensive tests covering all COBOL-85 features
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

@Reasoning:
Aggregated four-counter struct for the COBOL suite-of-suites driver.
Same layout as the JavaScript/C# variants so a unified runner can
consume any of them without struct conversion.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
total_suites at 0, passed_suites at 8, failed_suites at 16,
total_tests at 24. Mutated via Layout.memory_set_integer because the
struct is shared by handle.
@End Implementation

Type called "SuiteResults":
    total_suites as Integer
    passed_suites as Integer
    failed_suites as Integer
    total_tests as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Top-level orchestrator for the COBOL suite-of-suites. Five sub-suite
drivers cover the full pipeline (lex, parse, AST->HIR, HIR->COBOL,
round-trip). The five-stage breakdown means a CI failure immediately
diagnoses which compilation phase regressed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Initialize SuiteResults, print banner, then for each sub-suite:
print separator, call run_<phase>_tests, pass its return through
update_results. Final summary, return 1 on any failure.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All 5 sub-suite drivers return 0 -> total_suites=5, passed=5, exit 0
- Any sub-suite returns non-zero -> failed_suites += 1, exit 1
@End TestCases

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be a value of type SuiteResults with
        total_suites as 0,
        passed_suites as 0,
        failed_suites as 0,
        total_tests as 0

    proc print_main_header

    Note: Run lexer test suite
    proc print_suite_separator
    Let lexer_result be proc run_lexer_tests
    proc update_results with results, lexer_result, "Lexer Tests"

    Note: Run parser test suite
    proc print_suite_separator
    Let parser_result be proc run_parser_tests
    proc update_results with results, parser_result, "Parser Tests"

    Note: Run HIR translation test suite
    proc print_suite_separator
    Let hir_result be proc run_hir_tests
    proc update_results with results, hir_result, "HIR Translation Tests"

    Note: Run code generation test suite
    proc print_suite_separator
    Let codegen_result be proc run_codegen_tests
    proc update_results with results, codegen_result, "Code Generation Tests"

    Note: Run round-trip test suite
    proc print_suite_separator
    Let roundtrip_result be proc run_roundtrip_tests
    proc update_results with results, roundtrip_result, "Round-Trip Tests"

    proc print_suite_separator
    proc print_final_results from results

    If results.failed_suites is greater than 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatcher for the COBOL lexer test suite. Calls individual test_*
procs (defined elsewhere in the test infrastructure) and reports
the count of passed tests against the total. Returns 1 if all
sub-tests passed else 0.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Initialize test_count and passed_count to 0. For each test_* call,
increment test_count and increment passed_count if the test returned 1.
Return 1 if passed_count == test_count, else 0.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All sub-tests return 1 -> passed_count == test_count -> return 1
- Any sub-test returns 0 -> passed_count < test_count -> return 0
@End TestCases

Process called "run_lexer_tests" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
    Lexer tests verify complete COBOL tokenization:
    - All keywords (IDENTIFICATION, ENVIRONMENT, DATA, PROCEDURE, MOVE, etc.)
    - Division headers (IDENTIFICATION DIVISION, DATA DIVISION, etc.)
    - Level numbers (01-88)
    - Picture clauses (PIC X, PIC 9, PIC S9V99, etc.)
    - Number literals (decimal, signed)
    - String literals (single and double quotes)
    - Figurative constants (ZERO, SPACES, HIGH-VALUES, etc.)
    - Comments (asterisk in column 7 or inline)
    - Operators (arithmetic, relational, logical)
    - Punctuation (period, comma, parentheses)
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Execute comprehensive COBOL lexer test suite
    Let test_count be 0
    Let passed_count be 0

    Note: Test basic tokenization
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_cobol_basic_tokenization is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Test COBOL keywords
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_cobol_keywords is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Test literals and identifiers
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_cobol_literals_and_identifiers is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Test column-based parsing
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_cobol_column_parsing is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Test punctuation and operators
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_cobol_punctuation is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Return 1 if all tests passed, 0 otherwise
    If passed_count is equal to test_count:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatcher for the COBOL parser test suite. Same pattern as
run_lexer_tests: aggregates individual test_* procs and returns
the all-or-nothing pass/fail signal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Track test_count and passed_count. Each test_* call increments both
counters appropriately, then return 1 if all passed else 0.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All parser sub-tests pass -> return 1
- Any parser sub-test fails -> return 0
@End TestCases

Process called "run_parser_tests" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
    Parser tests verify complete AST generation:
    - Four divisions (IDENTIFICATION, ENVIRONMENT, DATA, PROCEDURE)
    - IDENTIFICATION DIVISION (PROGRAM-ID, AUTHOR, DATE-WRITTEN)
    - ENVIRONMENT DIVISION (CONFIGURATION, INPUT-OUTPUT, SELECT statements)
    - DATA DIVISION (FILE SECTION, WORKING-STORAGE, LINKAGE with data items)
    - PROCEDURE DIVISION (sections, paragraphs, all statements)
    - Data definitions (level numbers, PICTURE clauses, VALUE clauses)
    - All statement types (MOVE, ADD, COMPUTE, IF, PERFORM, DISPLAY, etc.)
    - File I/O (OPEN, CLOSE, READ, WRITE)
    - Control flow (IF-ELSE-END-IF, EVALUATE-WHEN, PERFORM-UNTIL, GO TO)
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Execute comprehensive COBOL parser test suite
    Let test_count be 0
    Let passed_count be 0

    Note: Test IDENTIFICATION DIVISION parsing
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_identification_division_parsing is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Test ENVIRONMENT DIVISION parsing
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_environment_division_parsing is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Test DATA DIVISION parsing
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_data_division_parsing is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Test PROCEDURE DIVISION parsing
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_procedure_division_parsing is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Test complete program parsing
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_complete_cobol_program_parsing is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Return 1 if all tests passed, 0 otherwise
    If passed_count is equal to test_count:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatcher for the COBOL AST -> HIR translation test suite. Same
aggregation pattern as the lexer and parser dispatchers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Track test_count and passed_count across all individual translation
tests; return 1 if all passed else 0.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All translation sub-tests pass -> return 1
- Any sub-test fails -> return 0
@End TestCases

Process called "run_hir_tests" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
    HIR translation tests verify COBOL AST → HIR conversion:
    - All division types correctly translated
    - Data items with level numbers and PICTURE preserved
    - Metadata preserved (level, picture, value)
    - Nested structures properly represented
    - Special COBOL features (paragraphs, sections, figurative constants)
    - Statement translation (all COBOL statement types)
    - Expression translation (arithmetic, relational, logical)
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Execute comprehensive HIR translation test suite
    Let test_count be 0
    Let passed_count be 0

    Note: Test AST to HIR conversion
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_cobol_ast_to_hir_conversion is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Test data structure translation
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_cobol_data_structure_translation is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Test statement translation
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_cobol_statement_translation is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Test expression translation
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_cobol_expression_translation is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Return 1 if all tests passed, 0 otherwise
    If passed_count is equal to test_count:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatcher for the HIR -> COBOL code generation test suite. Same
aggregation pattern. Catches emitter regressions that would corrupt
the canonical fixed-format COBOL output (column positions, period
placement, division headers).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Track test_count and passed_count across individual codegen tests;
return 1 if all passed else 0.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All codegen sub-tests pass -> return 1
- Any codegen test fails -> return 0
@End TestCases

Process called "run_codegen_tests" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
    Code generation tests verify HIR → COBOL code generation:
    - Idiomatic COBOL-85 output
    - Proper formatting (4-space indentation)
    - Uppercase keywords (COBOL convention)
    - Statement terminators (periods)
    - Division headers (IDENTIFICATION DIVISION, etc.)
    - Data definitions (level number + name + PIC + VALUE)
    - All statement types with correct syntax
    - Free-format COBOL output
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Execute comprehensive code generation test suite
    Let test_count be 0
    Let passed_count be 0

    Note: Test HIR to COBOL conversion
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_hir_to_cobol_conversion is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Test COBOL-85 compliance
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_cobol_85_compliance is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Test idiomatic COBOL output
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_idiomatic_cobol_output is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Return 1 if all tests passed, 0 otherwise
    If passed_count is equal to test_count:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatcher for the COBOL round-trip test suite. Verifies COBOL ->
HIR -> COBOL preserves program semantics; the inline @Reasoning
inside the body describes the COBOL-specific properties checked
(fixed-format alignment, IDENTIFICATION DIVISION preservation, etc).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Track test_count and passed_count across individual round-trip
tests; return 1 if all passed else 0.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All round-trip sub-tests pass -> return 1
- Any round-trip test fails -> return 0
@End TestCases

Process called "run_roundtrip_tests" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
    Round-trip tests verify COBOL → HIR → COBOL preservation:
    - Semantic equivalence maintained
    - Syntax may differ but meaning preserved
    - All COBOL features supported
    - Test programs: data definitions, arithmetic, file I/O, control flow
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Execute comprehensive round-trip test suite
    Let test_count be 0
    Let passed_count be 0

    Note: Test basic round-trip conversion
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_basic_cobol_round_trip is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Test complex program round-trip
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_complex_cobol_round_trip is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Test semantic preservation
    Set test_count to test_count plus 1
    If proc test_semantic_preservation is equal to 1:
        Set passed_count to passed_count plus 1
    End If

    Note: Return 1 if all tests passed, 0 otherwise
    If passed_count is equal to test_count:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Updates SuiteResults counters and prints per-suite pass/fail. Same
pattern as peer suite-of-suites drivers: centralizes bookkeeping
so all five run_*_tests calls feed through one update path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Increment total_suites at offset 0.
2. If suite_result == 0: increment passed_suites at offset 8, print
   "[SUITE PASSED] <name>".
3. Otherwise: increment failed_suites at offset 16, print
   "[SUITE FAILED] <name>".
@End Implementation

Process called "update_results" takes results as Integer, suite_result as Integer, suite_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let total be proc memory_get_integer with results, 0
    proc memory_set_integer with results, 0, total plus 1

    If suite_result is equal to 0:
        Let passed be proc memory_get_integer with results, 8
        proc memory_set_integer with results, 8, passed plus 1
        proc print_suite_success from suite_name
    Otherwise:
        Let failed be proc memory_get_integer with results, 16
        proc memory_set_integer with results, 16, failed plus 1
        proc print_suite_failure from suite_name
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Verbose suite banner. Prints title plus a list of the five sub-suites
with expected test counts so a CI consumer sees the work plan
before any tests execute.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate and print title "COBOL COMPREHENSIVE TEST SUITE", "="
separator (30 chars), info intro, then five "- <suite> (count)"
labels. Each string deallocated after print.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_main_header" returns Integer:
    Let header be proc create_string from StringCore with "COBOL COMPREHENSIVE TEST SUITE"
    proc print from header
    proc deallocate from Layout with header

    Let separator be proc create_string from StringCore with "================================"
    proc print from separator
    proc deallocate from Layout with separator

    Let info1 be proc create_string from StringCore with "Testing all COBOL-85 features:"
    proc print from info1
    proc deallocate from Layout with info1

    Let info2 be proc create_string from StringCore with "- Lexer (comprehensive tokenization)"
    proc print from info2
    proc deallocate from Layout with info2

    Let info3 be proc create_string from StringCore with "- Parser (complete AST generation)"
    proc print from info3
    proc deallocate from Layout with info3

    Let info4 be proc create_string from StringCore with "- HIR Translation (AST \u2192 HIR)"
    proc print from info4
    proc deallocate from Layout with info4

    Let info5 be proc create_string from StringCore with "- Code Generation (HIR \u2192 COBOL)"
    proc print from info5
    proc deallocate from Layout with info5

    Let info6 be proc create_string from StringCore with "- Round-Trip (50+ test programs)"
    proc print from info6
    proc deallocate from Layout with info6

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Visual separator between sub-suite runs. Same width as the main
banner for consistent visual structure in CI logs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Print empty line via empty string, then print 30-character "-" rule.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_suite_separator" returns Integer:
    Let separator be proc create_string from StringCore with ""
    proc print from separator
    proc deallocate from Layout with separator

    Let line be proc create_string from StringCore with "------------------------------------"
    proc print from line
    proc deallocate from Layout with line

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"[SUITE PASSED] <name>" line. Distinct from per-test [PASS].
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate "[SUITE PASSED] " prefix, print prefix and caller-owned
suite_name, deallocate the prefix.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_suite_success" takes suite_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "[SUITE PASSED] "
    proc print from msg
    proc print from suite_name
    proc deallocate from Layout with msg

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
"[SUITE FAILED] <name>" line. Distinct from per-test [FAIL].
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate "[SUITE FAILED] " prefix, print prefix and caller-owned
suite_name, deallocate the prefix.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_suite_failure" takes suite_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "[SUITE FAILED] "
    proc print from msg
    proc print from suite_name
    proc deallocate from Layout with msg

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Suite-of-suites final summary. Single human-readable verdict
("ALL TESTS PASSED!" or "SOME TESTS FAILED!") at the end of the log.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Print "=" header, "FINAL RESULTS:" heading, three counter lines
(Total/Passed/Failed Suites via print_int), then conditional verdict
line based on failed_suites == 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_final_results" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    Let header be proc create_string from StringCore with "================================"
    proc print from header
    proc deallocate from Layout with header

    Let summary be proc create_string from StringCore with "FINAL RESULTS:"
    proc print from summary
    proc deallocate from Layout with summary

    Let total_msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "Total Suites: "
    proc print from total_msg
    proc print_int with results.total_suites
    proc deallocate from Layout with total_msg

    Let passed_msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "Passed Suites: "
    proc print from passed_msg
    proc print_int with results.passed_suites
    proc deallocate from Layout with passed_msg

    Let failed_msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "Failed Suites: "
    proc print from failed_msg
    proc print_int with results.failed_suites
    proc deallocate from Layout with failed_msg

    If results.failed_suites is equal to 0:
        Let success be proc create_string from StringCore with "ALL TESTS PASSED!"
        proc print from success
        proc deallocate from Layout with success

    Otherwise:
        Let failure be proc create_string from StringCore with "SOME TESTS FAILED!"
        proc print from failure
        proc deallocate from Layout with failure
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Local integer formatter so this suite has no dependency on stdlib
formatting allocators. Zero and negative inputs handled explicitly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. value == 0 -> print "0", return.
2. Allocate 32-byte buffer; walk position 31 downward writing
   48 + (temp % 10), dividing temp by 10.
3. Negatives: operate on -temp; write '-' (45) at final position.
4. Increment position, print buffer+position, deallocate.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_int" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    If value is equal to 0:
        Let zero be proc create_string from StringCore with "0"
        proc print from zero
        proc deallocate from Layout with zero
        Return 1
    End If

    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    Let position be 31
    Let temp be value

    If temp is less than 0:
        Set temp to -temp
    End If

    While temp is greater than 0:
        Let digit be temp modulo by 10
        Let char be 48 plus digit
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, position, char
        Set position to position minus 1
        Set temp to temp divided by 10
    End While

    If value is less than 0:
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, position, 45
        Set position to position minus 1
    End If

    Set position to position plus 1
    Let str_ptr be buffer plus position
    proc print from str_ptr

    proc deallocate from Layout with buffer

    Return 1
End Process

Note: End of COBOL Comprehensive Test Suite Runner
